## Idea

An [[(âˆž,1)-category]] is _$n$-semiadditive_ for $n \in \mathbb{N}$ if [[(âˆž,1)-colimits]] over certain [[diagrams]] coincide with their [[(âˆž,1)-limits]] (see [Hopkins-Lurie 14, def. 4.4.2](#HopkinsLurie14)). Here for $n=0$ the condition is that [[coproducts]] coincide with [[products]], hence that [[bilimits]] exist.

So an [[(âˆž,1)-category]] that happens to be an ordinary [[category]] is 0-semiadditive precisely if it is a [[semiadditive category]] in the traditional sense. Generally, an [[(âˆž,1)-category]] is 0-semiadditive precisely if its [[homotopy category of an (âˆž,1)-category|homotopy category]] is [[semiadditive category|semiadditive]] ([Hopkins-Lurie 14, remark 4.4.13](#HopkinsLurie14)).

## Examples

* For $R$ an [[A-âˆž ring]] such that its connected component [[ring]] $\pi_0(A)$ is a [[vector space]] over the [[rational numbers]], then the [[(âˆž,1)-category of modules]] $A Mod$ is $n$-semiadditive for all $n \in \mathbb{N}$ ([Hopkins-Lurie 14, example 4.4.22](#HopkinsLurie14)).


## References

* {#HopkinsLurie14} [[Michael Hopkins]], [[Jacob Lurie]], _[[Ambidexterity in K(n)-Local Stable Homotopy Theory]]_ (2014)

